 subclavian artery, left common carotid artery, brachiocephalic trunk","Left common carotid artery, brachiocephalic trunk, left subclavian artery","Brachiocephalic trunk, left subclavian artery, left common carotid artery"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct sequence from proximal to distal is \u003Cstrong\u003Ebrachiocephalic trunk, left common carotid artery, left subclavian artery\u003C/strong\u003E. The brachiocephalic trunk must be first, and the left common carotid must come before the left subclavian.  The brachiocephalic trunk divides into the right common carotid and right subclavian arteries. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding this branching pattern is clinically important for interpreting radiological imaging and vascular surgery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The brachiocephalic trunk is the first branch of the aortic arch and divides into the right common carotid and right subclavian arteries.","The second branch of the aortic arch is the left common carotid artery","The left subclavian artery is the third branch of the aortic arch."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cBranches of the aorta\u201d by Mikael H\u00e4ggstr\u00f6m is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons\u00a0Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported\u00a0license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0) \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Aorta_branches.jpg\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64006"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17346"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21305"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21305"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/y6ysuktTekrtWSK6X6Eyvpfos7SZeq